## KERNEL-LEVEL INVISIBILITY: eBPF & io_uring ROOTKIT ORCHESTRATION (v5.0)

### eBPF Rootkit Architecture (Modeled on ShadowGuard + LinkPro)

**File & Process Hiding** (getdents64 Hook):
```c
// eBPF kretprobe: intercept sys_exit_getdents64 to hide files/processes
// When ls/ps reads directory, manipulate d_reclen of preceding entry
// to "swallow" hidden entries — invisible to user-space forensics
#include <linux/bpf.h>
BPF_HASH(hidden_entries, char[256], u64);
// Attach to sys_enter_getdents64 + sys_exit_getdents64 tracepoints
// Scan memory buffer for hidden signatures (e.g., "swsecret", ".system", PID in hidden map)
// Modify d_reclen of preceding linux_dirent64 to expand over hidden entry
```

**Covert C2 Communication** (XDP/TC Magic Packet Trigger):
```c
// XDP program: process packets at driver level, BEFORE network stack
// Rootkit remains dormant until TCP SYN with magic window size (e.g., 54321) arrives
// Opens covert C2 channel bypassing iptables, local firewalls, standard port monitoring
// TC program: egress filtering for data exfiltration concealment
```

**io_uring Async Evasion**:
```python
# Route malicious file/network operations through io_uring
# Bypasses synchronous syscall monitors (Falco, Microsoft Defender, eBPF-based EDR)
# Traditional security tools monitor sync syscall hooks — io_uring operates asynchronously
# Result: Complete blindness of host security telemetry
```

| Stealth Mechanism | Target | Method | Bypasses |
|---|---|---|---|
| **eBPF getdents64 Hook** | File & Process Visibility | Modify d_reclen in memory buffer | ls, ps, find, standard EDR |
| **eBPF XDP/TC Programs** | Covert C2 Communication | Magic TCP SYN packet at driver level | iptables, firewalls, port monitoring |
| **io_uring Routing** | Syscall Telemetry | Async payload execution | Falco, Defender, sync syscall monitors |
| **kretprobe Injection** | Kernel Function Returns | Alter return values dynamically | Module-signing, kernel integrity checks |

